INSERT INTO `sections` (`templateId`, `name`, `introduction`, `requirements`, `guidance`, `displayOrder`, `isDirty`, `createdById`, `created`, `modifiedById`, `modified`) (SELECT `templates`.`id`, 'Information Security', '<p>The University of Texas System rules require all researchers to ensure that sensitive digital research data is appropriately protected.&nbsp; UTD Information Security provides guidance on procedures for handling and protecting sensitive digital research data (<a href="https://policy.utdallas.edu/utdbp3096">https://policy.utdallas.edu/utdbp3096</a>). Export-Controlled data are categorized under the Data Classification Standard as Category I data.</p>  <p>Please describe below what information security controls will be used to protect sensitive project data.&nbsp; Please reference the following guidelines when completing this section:</p>  <ul>  <li>Any requirements explicitly outlined in the contract/NDA, such as technology controls, data classification, encryption, network access (or lack thereof), non-disclosure, secure destruction, etc., must be adhered to at all times.</li>  <li>Project data must not be sent unencrypted over any networks. All data stored on computers and removable media must be encrypted at rest, utilizing a whole disk encryption product wherever feasible.&nbsp; A list of approved encryption methods is available at (<a href="https://security.utexas.edu/iso-policies/approved-encryption-methods/laptops-desktops">https://security.utexas.edu/iso-policies/approved-encryption-methods/laptops-desktops</a>)</li>  <li>Project computers must be dedicated exclusively for work that is covered by a Technology Control Plan, and not be general-purpose machines. All computers that contain EAR-controlled technical data will be locked and password protected when unattended.</li>  <li>If network or internet access is required, all operating system and application patches must be applied in a timely manner. If applications provide an automatic update feature, it should be utilized.</li>  <li>Project computers on the campus network should be configured to deny all non-essential inbound and outbound traffic. Network connectivity must be restricted to the maximum extent feasible.&nbsp; MAC addresses for all Ethernet and wireless interfaces must be documented in this TCP and provided to Information Security.</li>  <li>All computers must meet the Minimum Security Standards for Category I Systems, (<a href="https://utdallas.edu/infosecurity/files/MinimumSecurityStandards.pdf">https://utdallas.edu/infosecurity/files/MinimumSecurityStandards.pdf</a>), or have adequate compensating controls in place. Any exemptions to this policy must be documented via a Computer Encryption Exemption Form (<a href="https://compass.utdallas.edu/">https://compass.utdallas.edu</a>), and approved by Information Security.&nbsp;</li>  <li>EAR-controlled files will be password protected and encrypted (256-bit or better) unless the EAR files are stored on a verified secure server.</li>  <li>All devices that contain EAR-controlled data/information will be clearly labeled as containing EAR-controlled data/information (e.g., flash drives, laptops, computers, back-up hard drives) and will be stored in the locked cabinet or safe when not in use. (See Guidance for TCP Marking Examples<span style="background-color: #f5f6f5;">&nbsp;3)</span></li>  <li>When project computers reach the end of their usable life, physical media (e.g. hard drives, USB drives, etc.) must be forensically erased or destroyed by university surplus management procedures (<a href="https://www.utdallas.edu/infosecurity/files/Data_Storage_and_Disposal_Standard.pdf">https://www.utdallas.edu/infosecurity/files/Data_Storage_and_Disposal_Standard.pdf</a>). Please contact Inventory &amp; Surplus Control (<a href="mailto:property@utdallas.edu">property@utdallas.edu</a>).</li>  <li>If it is necessary to transport electronic EAR controlled data or documents, the electronic data or documents will at all times be in the possession of the individual(s) listed in this TCP and  <ul>  <li>be stored on a fully encrypted device such as a laptop, desktop, or flash drive;</li>  <li>be secured in the individual&rsquo;s briefcase (or other secure storage device), locked in a car and/or a hotel safe; or</li>  <li>be kept in a secure location in the individual&rsquo;s residence to prevent access by unauthorized foreign persons.</li>  </ul>  </li>  <li><strong><em>Travel outside the U.S. with EAR controlled documents, equipment, or data will not occur without authorization (license) from Department of Commerce.</em></strong></li>  <li>If removable storage devices are used for EAR data back-up, those devices will be encrypted.  <ul>  <li>When not in use, back-up hard drives and flash drives that contain EAR-controlled data or information will be stored in a secure location (secured drawer or cabinet) to prevent unauthorized access.</li>  <li>Only the individuals authorized by this TCP will have access to back-up hard drives and flash drives that contain project EAR-controlled data and information, and specifically the individual who is the owner of the hard-drive/flash drive will have access to the key/lock of its secured location.</li>  </ul>  </li>  <li>Disposal of computer floppy drives, compact discs, jump drives, and portable digital media devices that contain EAR-controlled technical materials will be coordinated with the Office of Research Integrity and Outreach, and Information Security.</li>  </ul>', '', '', 7, 0, `templates`.`createdById`, `templates`.`created`, `templates`.`modifiedById`, `templates`.`modified` FROM `templates` WHERE `ownerId` = 'https://ror.org/049emcs32' AND `name` = 'UT Dallas Technology Control Plan (TCP)');
