INSERT INTO `templates` (`name`, `description`, `ownerId`, `visibility`, `currentVersion`, `isDirty`, `bestPractice`, `createdById`, `created`, `modifiedById`, `modified`) (SELECT 'Duke University Data Management Plan Template and Guidance V1 2020', '<p><strong>***THIS VERSION OF THE DUKE DMP TEMPLATE AND GUIDANCE WILL BE SUNSETTED ON MAY 31, 2022. PLEASE USE THE NEW VERSION 2 PLAN (SELECT FIRST OPTION IN DROP DOWN).***</strong></p> <p>This Data Management Planning template was created by the Duke University Office of Scientific Integrity and Duke University Libraries. It is designed to help you construct a Data Management Plan (DMP) for your lab, your research team, or for yourself. Your DMP should address each of the major questions within all five phases (tabs listed above). Guidance on best practices for how to answer each question are included with the appropriate phase.&nbsp;</p> <p>Depending on your research, your DMP may cover your entire research unit (laboratory, team) or be focused on a specific project. Due to funder, publisher, or Duke institutional requirements (e.g., Research Data Storage Plan for clinical trials), you may have documented elements of your data management plan elsewhere. Please reference those documents as applicable. Although the DMP guidance document focuses mostly on digital data, it may also be pertinent to develop management plans for other important data resources (e.g., specimens, code, custom instruments). Once drafted, revisit your DMP regularly (at least every 2 years) to ensure it still meets the needs of the research team and/or the research being conducted in your unit.</p> <p><strong>IF YOU ARE WRITING A DMP FOR A FUNDING AGENCY, PLEASE CHECK THE DMPTOOL TO SEE IF THERE IS A SPECIFIC TEMPLATE FOR YOUR FUNDER. IF NOT, PLEASE CONTACT US: datamanagement@duke.edu</strong></p> <p><strong>Key Definitions:</strong></p> <ul> <li><strong>Data Ownership and Stewardship:</strong> Data ownership is a legal concept of who has the legal rights to<br />the data. Duke is generally considered the primary owner of all data generated at Duke (Faculty<br />Handbook P-31). Data stewardship refers to the responsibilities taken for management and oversight<br />of the data. Commonly, researchers who generate or have access to the data act as data stewards.<br /><br /></li> <li><strong>Data and Source Data:</strong> Data are the "the recorded factual material commonly accepted in the<br />scientific community as necessary to validate research findings" (OMB Circular 110). Source data are<br />the original records or certified copies of original records used to support research findings.<br /><br /></li> <li><strong>Primary Data:</strong> When a researcher or research team generates/collects their data themselves, it is<br />considered primary data. Although a researcher may collect their own data, they still may not be the<br />owner of the primary data, depending on the source of the data/materials collected.<br /><br /></li> <li><strong>Secondary Data:</strong> When a researcher or research team uses data generated previously, that is<br />considered secondary data. Secondary data could be a dataset generated by a member of your<br />research team at an earlier time, or could be from a completely independent unit, such as another<br />center&rsquo;s database, archive, or repository.<br /><br /></li> <li><strong>Documentation:</strong> Documentation is the description or recording of the research project, methods,<br />results, and analyses that allows someone to understand the context of both the data (how they were<br />obtained/derived) and the research process. The term &ldquo;documentation&rdquo; may be more recognizable<br />when referred to by discipline specific names, such as lab notebooks, methodology reports, protocols,<br />codebooks or data dictionaries, user guides or data narratives, README files, wikis, etc.<br /><br /></li> <li><strong>Metadata:</strong> Metadata are the contextual details about the data (i.e., data about the data). Metadata<br />are critical to understanding data and reproducing research results. Formal metadata are structured <br />through a standard or schema. Structured standards and schemas allow for data discoverability (item <br />record in a repository) and interoperability (shared fields and terminology). Examples of structured <br />metadata include Dublin Core (general), the Data Documentation Initiative (DDI) (social sciences), <br />and Darwin Core (biological sciences).<br /><br /></li> <li><strong>Data Resources:</strong> Data resources (e.g., reagents, samples, tools, software, code and associated<br />metadata) are the elements that are produced/generated as part of a research project.<br /><br /></li> <li><strong>Data Lifecycle</strong>: The full lifecycle for data from initiation through preservation. Throughout this <br />template we reference phases within the lifecycle:&nbsp;<br /> <ul> <li>Data Planning and Collection: Where you plan your research and collect/generate data,<br />metadata and data resources to address a research question.</li> <li>Data Processing (or Data Cleaning): Where you organize your analysis workflow, code (or<br />recode) variables, structure (or restructure) files, and address any problems or errors, such as<br />missing data or instrument calibration issues in the event you need to recollect data.</li> <li>Data Analysis: Where you apply quantitative, qualitative or other relevant analysis techniques<br />to test your hypotheses and/or research questions.</li> <li>Data Sharing or Publishing: Where data are shared with the scientific community and/or<br />made public through a repository or archive.</li> <li>Data Archiving: When data are moved to a more permanent location for retention and<br />preservation after the conclusion of the project.</li> </ul> </li> </ul> <p><a title="Duke Data Management Resources Table" href="https://portal.dh.duke.edu/som/asist/Shared%20Documents/DMPGD_Duke%20Data%20Management%20Resources.xlsx?Web=1">Duke Data Management Resources Table</a></p>', 'https://ror.org/00py81415', 'PRIVATE', 'v3', 0, 0, `users`.`id`, '2020-01-06 20:23:48', `users`.`id`, '2022-04-18 21:03:53' FROM `users` WHERE `affiliationId` = 'https://ror.org/00py81415' AND `role` = 'ADMIN');
