INSERT INTO `sections` (`templateId`, `name`, `introduction`, `requirements`, `guidance`, `displayOrder`, `isDirty`, `createdById`, `created`, `modifiedById`, `modified`) (SELECT `templates`.`id`, 'Data storage and long-term preservation', '<p>Describe what physical and/or cyber resources and facilities (including third party resources) will be used to store and preserve the data during the lifetime of the grant. Also, describe your long-term strategy for archiving and preserving the data you collect or use. Questions to address when writing this section:</p>  <ul>  <li>Where will the working data (that currently being collected or analyzed) be stored during the research period?</li>  <li>What procedures are in place for backing up the working data?</li>  <li>What is the long-term strategy for maintaining, curating and archiving the data?</li>  <li>Which archive/repository/database have you identified as a place to deposit data?</li>  <li>What procedures does your intended long-term data storage facility have in place for preservation and backup?</li>  <li>How long will/should data be kept beyond the life of the project?</li>  <li>What transformations will be necessary to prepare data for preservation / data sharing?</li>  <li>What related information will be deposited?</li>  </ul>  <p>How the Libraries can help: For working data, ARCC provides free storage up to 500 GB for data from an active research project on the Data Commons, and this storage can scale larger depending on researchers needs. Researchers also have access to OneDrive at the University. For long-term storage, the UW Libraries can provide expertise and resources. Some disciplines, grants, and publishers request or require researchers to use a specific external data repository. The Libraries can help researchers locate such repositories and prepare their data for deposit. Additionally, the Libraries also maintains a non-discipline specific data repository for the University called Mountain Scholar. As part of an agreement with ARCC, Mountain Scholar offers a robust storage solution to meet the University of Wyoming researchers&rsquo; needs. Research data is stored on the petaLibrary, and Mountain Scholar is the access user interface where you and others can see and access your data. Mountain Scholar can store not only the published data, but also associated documentation, metadata, and even publications.</p>', '', '', 2, 0, `templates`.`createdById`, `templates`.`created`, `templates`.`modifiedById`, `templates`.`modified` FROM `templates` WHERE `ownerId` = 'https://ror.org/01485tq96' AND `name` = 'UW-Resource Specific Template');
