INSERT INTO `sections` (`templateId`, `name`, `introduction`, `requirements`, `guidance`, `displayOrder`, `isDirty`, `createdById`, `created`, `modifiedById`, `modified`) (SELECT `templates`.`id`, 'Data dissemination and sharing (internally and externally)', '<p>It is the responsibility of researchers and institutions to make results, data, derived data products, and collections available to the research community in a timely manner. Data may be made available for secondary use through submission to a national data center, publication in a widely available journal, book/website, discipline-specific data repository, or an institutional archive. Specify how you will share your data with others after the project is completed. Regardless of the repository you choose, describe how you chose it. Questions to address when writing this section:</p>  <ul>  <li>How, when, and where will you make the data available? (Include resources needed to make the data available: equipment, systems, expertise, etc.)</li>  <li>What resources will be needed to reuse the data? Examples include software or equipment.</li>  <li>What is the process for gaining access to the data?</li>  <li>Who are the foreseeable data users?</li>  <li>How should your data be cited?</li>  <li>How long will the original data collector/creator/principal investigator retain the right to use the data before opening it up to wider use?</li>  <li>Explain details of any embargo periods for political/commercial/patent or publisher reasons.</li>  </ul>  <p>How the Libraries can help: Occasionally, the best course of action for sharing data is using a discipline specific external data repository. However, if you decide to keep your data on campus, Mountain Scholar may be your solution. If you deposit your research data in Mountain Scholar, you also will receive a long-term unique identifier, a DOI. This identifier allows your data to be more easily findable and cited. For internal sharing, the petaLibrary has a Globus Online endpoint (https://www.globus.org/). Globus is a Dropbox-like tool that allows users to transfer very large datasets fairly quickly through a grid FTP method. Additionally, Globus allows researchers to control access to their data with a web based user management application.</p>', '', '', 4, 0, `templates`.`createdById`, `templates`.`created`, `templates`.`modifiedById`, `templates`.`modified` FROM `templates` WHERE `ownerId` = 'https://ror.org/01485tq96' AND `name` = 'UW-Resource Specific Template');
